<|channel>thought
<channel|>"Biographies of 張釋之 and 馮唐"

The 廷尉 張釋之 was a person from 堵陽, courtesy name 季. He had an elder brother named 仲 who lived with him. Because of his criticism, he served as a 騎郎; he served 孝文帝, but for ten years he was not transferred and had no renown. 張釋之 said, "Long service in officialdom diminishes the property of 仲, which is not good." He wished to resign and return home. The 中郎將 袁盎 knew his virtue and regretted his departure, so he requested to transfer 張釋之 to serve as an 謁者. After 張釋之 finished his court duties, he took the opportunity to speak of matters of convenience. 文帝 said, "Lower your tone; do not offer lofty arguments, so that they may be implemented now." Thus, 張釋之 spoke of matters from the interval between 秦 and Han, explaining why 秦 lost and why Han rose, for a long time. 文帝 praised him and appointed 張釋之 as 謁者仆射.

張釋之 accompanied the travels and ascended the 虎圈. The Emperor asked about the registers of birds and beasts of the 上林尉; after more than ten questions, the 尉 and his attendants looked at each other, none able to answer. A 嗇夫 of the 虎圈 from the side answered the Emperor's questions regarding the registers of birds and beasts very thoroughly, intending to show his ability to respond endlessly to spoken words. 文帝 said, "Should officials not be like this? The 尉 is useless!" He then issued an edict appointing 張釋之 to make the 嗇夫 the 上林令. Previously, 張釋之 had asked, "What does Your Majesty think of the 絳侯 周勃?" The Emperor said, "He is a person of character (長者)." He asked again, "What do you think of the 東陽侯 張相?" The Emperor replied again, "A person of character." 張釋之 said, "To call the 絳侯 and the 東陽侯 persons of character—these two men could not even speak their minds on matters, how can they be compared to this 嗇夫 who is talkative and quick-witted? Furthermore, 秦 relied on officials of the knife and brush, and these officials competed to be most rapid and harsh in their inspections; however, their flaws were merely in their written formalities, lacking the reality of compassion. Because of this, one did not hear of their errors, and they declined gradually until the second generation, causing the world to collapse. Now Your Majesty, because of a 嗇夫's eloquence, promotes him rapidly; I fear the world will follow this trend, competing in eloquence without reality. Moreover, the influence of those below on those above is swifter than an echo; the appointment of 錯 must be examined carefully." 文帝 said, "Good." He then ceased and did not appoint the 嗇夫.

The Emperor approached the carriage and summoned 張釋之 to ride with him. As they traveled slowly, the Emperor asked 張釋之 about the flaws of 秦. He answered in detail with substance. Upon reaching the palace, the Emperor appointed 張釋之 as 公車令.

Shortly after, the 太子 and the 梁王 shared a carriage to enter the court, but did not descend at the 司馬門; thus, 張釋之 pursued and stopped the 太子 and 梁王, preventing them from entering the hall gates. He then impeached them, saying that not descending at the official gates was disrespectful, and submitted the report. 薄太后 heard of this; 文帝 removed his cap and apologized, saying, "I failed to teach my sons with caution." 薄太后 then sent an envoy to carry the edict to pardon the 太子 and 梁王, after which they were allowed to enter. From this, 文帝 regarded 張釋之 as extraordinary and appointed him as 中大夫.

Shortly after, he reached the rank of 中郎將. He accompanied the travels to 霸陵 and resided north, facing the latrines. At this time, 慎夫人 accompanied them. The Emperor pointed out the 新豐道 to 慎夫人, saying, "This is the road that leads to 邯鄲." He had 慎夫人 play the 瑟, and the Emperor leaned against the 瑟 and sang, his mood tragic and sorrowful. He looked at the officials and said, "Alas! To use stones from the 北山 as a coffin, to use 紵 and 絮 to line it, and to lacquer the gaps—how can this be moved?" Those around him all said, "Good." 張釋之 stepped forward and said, "If there is something desirable within it, even if it is encased in 南山, there is still a gap; if there is nothing desirable within it, even without a stone coffin, why be sorrowful!" 文帝 praised him. Later, he was appointed as 廷尉.

Shortly after, the Emperor traveled out of the 中渭橋. A man emerged from under the bridge, causing the imperial carriage and horses to startle. The Emperor ordered the cavalry to capture him and entrusted the matter to the 廷尉. 張釋之 conducted the investigation and said, "A man from the county heard the imperial procession and hid under the bridge. After a long time, thinking the procession had passed, he emerged, saw the imperial carriage and cavalry, and immediately ran." The 廷尉 秦當 said, "One person violated the imperial procession; the penalty should be a fine of gold." 文帝 was angry and said, "This person personally startled my horses. My horses are naturally gentle; if I used other horses, would they not have broken or injured me? Yet the 廷尉 intends to punish him with a fine!" 張釋之 said, "The law is that which the Son of Heaven shares with the world. If the law is like this and is made even heavier, the law will not be trusted by the people. Furthermore, at that moment, if Your Majesty had ordered him executed immediately, it would have been done. Now that the matter has been passed to the 廷尉, the 廷尉 is the arbiter of the world; if he tilts, the weight of the law for the whole world shifts. Where can the people find stability? I beg Your Majesty to examine this." After a long time, the Emperor said, "The 廷尉 is correct."

Later, someone stole the jade rings from the front seats of the 高廟. When captured, 文帝 was angry and sent the matter to the 廷尉. 張釋之 examined the statutes and reported that those who steal ritual objects of the ancestral temple should be sent to execution by public decapitation. The Emperor was greatly angered and said, "The person is lawless for stealing the ritual objects of the 先帝's temple. We, who have the 廷尉, wish to execute his entire clan, yet you report it according to the law; this is not in accordance with our intention to uphold the ancestral temple." 張釋之 removed his cap, prostrated himself, and apologized, saying, "The law is sufficient as it is. Although the crimes are of a certain grade, there is a difference between rebellion and non-rebellion. Now, if a thief of ancestral objects is executed with his clan, even if it happens once in ten thousand, if a commoner were to take a handful of earth from 長陵, how would the law punish him?" After a long time, 文帝 discussed this with the 太后, and they permitted the 廷尉's judgment. At this time, the 中尉 條侯 周亞夫 and the 梁相 山都侯 王恬 became friends with 張釋之 after seeing his impartial judgment. Because of this, the world praised 廷尉 張.

Later, 文帝 died, 景帝 was established, and 張釋之, fearing for his safety, claimed illness. He wished to resign, fearing a great purge; he wished to visit and apologize, but did not know how. He lived by the means of 王生. Ultimately, he visited and apologized; 景帝 was not a man of such temperament.

王生 was skilled in the teachings of 黃老 and was a scholar living in retirement. He was once summoned to reside in the imperial court, where the 三公 and 九卿 all gathered to stand. 王生 was an old man and said, "I am old and my hair is gray," then looked at 廷尉 張 and said, "Tie a 絤 for me!" 張釋之 knelt and tied it. Once finished, someone said to 王生, "How could you so insult 張釋之 in court by making him kneel to tie a 絤?" 王生 said, "I am old and lowly; I judge that my end will be of no benefit to 張釋之. 張釋之 is a famous official of the world today; I merely insulted the 廷尉 by making him kneel to tie a 絤, intending to honor him." The officials heard this and esteemed 王生 and respected 張釋之.

廷尉 張 served 景帝 for over a year and was the 相 of 淮南王, yet he still held onto his previous ways. After a long time, 張釋之 died. His son was 張摯, courtesy name 長公, who reached the rank of 大夫 and was dismissed. Because he could not win favor in his era, he did not serve in office for the rest of his life.

馮唐's grandfather was a person from 趙. His father moved to 代. When Han rose, they moved to 安陵. 馮唐 was famous for filial piety and served as 中郎署長, serving 文帝. As 文帝's carriage passed, he asked 馮唐, "Why is an elder serving as a 郎? Where is your home?" 馮唐 answered truthfully. 文帝 said, "When I lived in 代, the 尚食監 高袪 once told me of the virtue of the 趙 general 李齊, who fought below 鉅鹿. Now, every time I eat, my mind is never not at 鉅鹿. Do you know this?" 馮唐 replied, "He is not as good as 廉頗 or 李牧 in being a general." The Emperor said, "Why?" 馮唐 said, "My grandfather, when in 趙, was an official (soldier) [leading] troops and was fond of 李牧. My father was formerly the 相 of 代 and was fond of the 趙 general 李齊, and knew his character." Having heard of the character of 廉頗 and 李牧, the Emperor was very pleased and struck his thighs, saying, "Alas! If only I had 廉頗 and 李牧 as my generals in my time, how could I worry about the 匈奴!" 馮唐 said, "Master and subject! Even if Your Majesty had 廉頗 and 李牧, you would not have been able to use them." The Emperor was angry and rose to enter the inner palace. After a long time, he summoned 馮唐 and rebuked him, saying, "How could you so publicly insult me? Do you have no sense of propriety?" 馮唐 apologized, saying, "This lowly person did not know the taboos."

At this time, the 匈奴 had newly entered the court at 那, killing the 北地都尉 卬. The Emperor, preoccupied with the barbarian bandits, finally asked 馮唐 again, "How do you know that I could not use 廉頗 and 李牧?" 馮唐 replied, "I have heard that in ancient times, when a King dispatched a general, he would kneel and push the axle of a chariot and say: 'Within the threshold, I control; outside the threshold, the General controls.' Military merits and rewards are all decided outside, and are reported upon returning. This is not an empty saying. My grandfather said that when 李牧 was a 趙 general on the frontier, the taxes from the military markets were all used to reward the soldiers; rewards and gifts were decided outside, without interference from the center. By delegating authority and demanding success, 李牧 was able to exhaust his intelligence. He selected one thousand three hundred chariots, thirteen thousand cavalry, one hundred thousand elite soldiers of a hundred gold pieces; thus, he drove the 單于 to the north, defeated the 東胡, destroyed 澹林, suppressed the 彊秦 to the west, and supported 韓 and 魏 to the south. At that time, 趙 was nearly a hegemon. Later, when the 趙王 遷 was established, his mother was a woman of loose character. When 遷 was established, he used the slanders of 郭開, and ultimately executed 李牧, replacing him with 顏聚. Because of this, the army was broken and the soldiers fled north, and they were captured and destroyed by 秦. Now, I have heard that the 魏 official 魏尚 serves as the 雲中守; the taxes from his military markets are all used to reward the soldiers, and he uses his own money to support them, slaughtering an ox every five days to feast guests, military officers, and attendants; thus, the 匈奴 avoid him and do not approach the passes of 雲中. When the captives once entered, he led chariots and cavalry to strike them, killing many. The soldiers are all sons and brothers of families, rising from the fields to join the army; how could they know the registers and tally marks? They fight hard all day, taking heads and prisoners to report merits to the government, yet if one word does not match, the clerks punish them according to the law. Their rewards are not implemented, while the officials must strictly follow the law. I am foolish, but I believe Your Majesty's laws are too clear, the rewards too light, and the punishments too heavy. Furthermore, the 雲中守 魏尚 was granted six levels of merit for his achievements, yet Your Majesty, if an official falls, reduces his rank and imposes punishment. From this, even if Your Majesty had 廉頗 and 李牧, you would not be able to use them. I am truly foolish and have touched upon taboos; it is a capital offense, a capital offense!" 文帝 was pleased. On that day, he ordered 馮唐 to carry an edict to pardon 魏尚, reappoint him as 雲中守, and appointed 馮唐 as 車騎都尉, in charge of the 中尉 and the chariots and cavalry of the commanderies and kingdoms.

In the seventh year, 景帝 was established, and 馮唐 was appointed as the 相 of 楚, then dismissed. When 武帝 was established, he sought the worthy and recommended 馮唐. 馮唐 was then over ninety years old and could not serve as an official again, so he appointed 馮唐's son 馮遂 as a 郎. 遂, courtesy name 王孫, was also an extraordinary man and was a friend of mine.

The 太史公 says: The words of 張季之 regarding persons of character, who uphold the law without bowing to personal whims; and the discourse of 馮公 regarding the leadership of generals, are flavorful! How flavorful! There is a saying: "If you do not know a person, look at his friends." The praises of these two men are worthy of being displayed in the imperial halls. The Book says: "Without bias and without factions, the Kingly Way is vast and expansive; without factions and without bias, the Kingly Way is smooth and easy." 張季 and 馮公 are close to this. [end of text]


